build 2.6 teams.

00:52:40.290 --> 00:52:42.540
What they essentially do
is they place fellows.

00:52:42.540 --> 00:52:44.637
They hate when I use this
analogy but it works.

00:52:44.637 --> 00:52:46.220
They're sort of like
Teach for America

00:52:46.220 --> 00:52:47.960
but for city and
state governments.

00:52:47.960 --> 00:52:50.940
So they try and place mid-career
professionals and entrepreneurs

00:52:50.940 --> 00:52:52.720
into city and state
governments in order

00:52:52.720 --> 00:52:54.157
to bring those fresh ideas in.

00:52:54.157 --> 00:52:56.240
The other thing I think a
lot of industrial design

00:52:56.240 --> 00:52:58.580
and consulting firms
have a structure

00:52:58.580 --> 00:53:00.020
that allows them to do that.

00:53:00.020 --> 00:53:02.506
Roger Martin from the Rotman
School up in Toronto actually

00:53:02.506 --> 00:53:04.880
had this great article a couple
months ago in the Harvard

00:53:04.880 --> 00:53:07.540
Business Review around,
even economically there

00:53:07.540 --> 00:53:10.301
may be a case for the
consultancy firm model,

00:53:10.301 --> 00:53:12.800
where people are always moving
around to different projects.

00:53:12.800 --> 00:53:15.080
Because when you have an
economic downturn, if you've

00:53:15.080 --> 00:53:17.550
structured boxes and lines in
a traditional hierarchy then

00:53:17.550 --> 00:53:19.508
you look and go, this
segment's not performing.

00:53:19.508 --> 00:53:20.680
We spit it off.

00:53:20.680 --> 00:53:23.100
But if you have a much more
fluid structure than you

00:53:23.100 --> 00:53:25.849
can adapt quicker and possibly
not lay as many people off

00:53:25.849 --> 00:53:27.890
and then have to scramble
to find new people when

00:53:27.890 --> 00:53:28.644
it comes back.

00:53:28.644 --> 00:53:29.560
That's where it sucks.

00:53:29.560 --> 00:53:31.143
So there's maybe
even an economic case

00:53:31.143 --> 00:53:33.912
to be made for that
little bit more fluid.

00:53:33.912 --> 00:53:36.849
We're really at the
beginning of figuring out

00:53:36.849 --> 00:53:39.140
what does this model look
like, because it doesn't look

00:53:39.140 --> 00:53:42.800
like boxes and lines and
factory assembly lines

00:53:42.800 --> 00:53:45.190
and that sort of stuff.

